Superdan

2013-01-02 18:33:00 UTC
Im clearly no expert over the mountain but it takes BALLs to do it quick.

Hug the inside kerb and you are faced with a wall of tarmac it looks tame on video but it's steep, you can gun it over the middle where most get air and it naturally leads you to that point anyway as you gas it up, or you can take it slightly to the left or right if you want to overtake someone as its only 75m to next corner.

As im not very good at wheelying im not used to front coming up so roll off the throttle a little bit more than the others, my front floats over the top and I just pin it. The small straight then dips down slightly so easy to hold the wheelie or loft it again.

You cannot keep the throttle pinned all the way over you would just flip the bike, those who jump it probably let the gas off a little later than me as the front rises and literally the momentum lifts the rear.

However with my method and some of the others there is not much time to be lost and made really.

What shocks me most is the patterns. By that I mean that one sees the same type of thing happening
over and over again. I guess that is what experience is - you've seen it all before and thus recognise the
dangers and avoid them. Certainly, there is lack of roadcraft but so many are all the same thing. I guess
that is why riding courses talk about the dangers but seeing twenty or thirty in the same video is somewhat
compelling. Here in Oz Mick Doohan has made a TV advert about the dangers of intersections but maybe
seeing the same thing over and over again is pretty compelling.

Notes to self: Don't ride in the former Soviet Union. Continue to wear helmet and full leathers. Don't
ride with boy racers that target fixate - correction - don't ride with boy racers.

Lowrance

2013-12-05 17:20:00 UTC
With all the back and forth about the cheers and jeers for bike electronic features, I saw this and thought it was an interesting example of old/new school racers. I like how Marquez speaks of this difference and acknowledges the skill Spencer had in racing bikes of his day (7:40), highlighting the application of electronics/suspension/etc. I'm no expert, but it seems all electronics aim to temper a machine's raw performance into something that hopefully results in better actual performance (ABS modulating hard braking without locking up, TC to drop power during a spin, etc). I can see how factory out of box electronic settings might actually be a hindrance to a brain that fully anticipates the bike to behave in a certain way with the twist of the throttle or squeeze of the brake. Likewise, i'm sure it'd be scary for the inexperienced/unprepared to ride something like a S1000 or SD1290 on full power. So much of riding a motorcycle safely and fast depends on the rider being able to accurately judge and anticipate outcomes and NOT be surprised at any point.

Hey stel I'm not bagging you out about how you ride.
Dont get me wrong as I'm as guilty as most moto riders of going fast.
I think the main problem is that bikes can get up to high speed in little distance so to go up to 160kph 100mph is no big deal but the proplem is and I think a lot more about it theses days as I'm getting older is the unforeseen situations.
A rider can ride fast like in the videos you posted but only for so long before it all goes wrong just a bit of gravel on a corner that wasn't there last time you did those bends can make all the difference.
Also if you've never had the good fortune of laying in a hostpital bed waiting on your body to recover from injury's well its all more the fun taking risks but if you have been in hospital for a time it makes you think differently.
You might think well I've been riding like this for 5 or more years with no problems.
I can tell you its all just a matter of time before it all goes ass up. Nearly every rider I know has had at least one crash and walked away but for some it was the one that took their life.
Stay safe

PBRnr

2016-05-24 17:34:00 UTC
https://www.superbike-coach.com/portfol ... lie-course

Fun day on a small course in Stockton, CA. They offer a lot of casual (but really helpful and constructive, no BS) feedback. You can rent a bike with a wheelie bar for the whole day, but if you do not want that, you still get to take turns on a wheelie bike and pocket bike when you are not riding your own.

My only critique is that the "sessions" are a bit long (25 minutes) which is great time riding/practicing, however seems like an eternity when your group is on break, sitting and watching others go at it.
